_blank\">This ought to be the Climate Change election</a>.  Let\'s make it one.  Vote for Kenney.\r\n\r\n- gather articles abt Kenney\r\n- show he listens and cares\r\n- show his evolution\r\n- list env orgs endorsing him\r\n- photo w muslim leaders\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;','the Climate election in Philadelphia','','inherit','open','open','','246-revision-v1','','','2015-05-13 12:14:01','2015-05-13 12:14:01','',246,'http://brightphillyfuture.bowersad.com/index.php/2015/05/13/246-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(249,2,'2015-05-13 12:21:39','2015-05-13 12:21:39','Next Tuesday, May 19th, are the primaries.  Philadelphians, predominantly democratic, get to nominate one of the 6 democratic candidates for our next Mayor. The lineup includes Jim Kenney, Nelson Diaz, Lynne Abraham, Anthony Williams, and Doug Oliver &amp; Milton Street. Whoever wins in the primaries next week in effect becomes our next Mayor after the November elections. Of the 6, Jim Kenney rises to the top.\r\n\r\nKenney listens to the people. Even people different from him. Examples abound in his openness to LGBT rights, to marijuana reform, to immigration reform. And now, to preparing for climate disruption.\r\n\r\nAs true intelligence is demonstrated by patient listening, mayoral candidate Jim Kenney has listened and has recently added a trio of forward thinking sustainable energy professionals to his policy team. Philadelphians respect an open and democratic process for our energy future and applaud Kenney’s action. Jim Kenney wants to see our city continue forward as a green and clean historic destination, thereby he has made carbon reduction a top priority.\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>On May 11th, the Daily News <a href=\"http://www.philly.com/philly/news/politics/mayor/20150511_DN_Editorial__DAILY_NEWS_ENDORSEMENT__FOR_MAYOR__JIM_KENNEY.html\" target=\"_blank\">editorial</a> wrote this: \"Kenney has shown himself to be independent, especially when you consider the lack of support for many of his pet causes. He knows how the city and its politics work, and is smart and open to new ideas.\"</li>\r\n	<li>On May 7th, the Inquirer wrote <a href=\"http://articles.philly.com/2015-05-07/news/61869256_1_jim-kenney-police-brutality-civilian-review-board\" target=\"_blank\">this</a>: Kenney called passionate, loyal to a fault, driven to do right.</li>\r\n	<li>On May 3rd, Philadelphia Magazine article <a href=\"http://www.phillymag.com/news/2015/05/03/jim-kenney-mayor-endorsement/\" target=\"_blank\">The (New) Jim Kenney for Mayor</a></li>\r\n	<li>On April 24th, GRID magazine <a href=\"http://www.gridphilly.com/grid-magazine/2015/4/24/grid-endorses-nelson-diaz-for-mayor.html\">endorses Nelson Diaz for Mayor</a>.  Many of us were disappointed to see this from a local magazine educating our region on sustainability.  We\'ve since realized that this was before the Kenney energy policy was public. The Kenney policy is much better, we think; not just because we helped craft it! And, last we heard, Diaz only had 4% at the polls.</li>\r\n	<li>On Feb 26th Philadelphia Magazine article <a href=\"http://www.phillymag.com/citified/2015/02/26/heavy-hitters-jim-kenneys-new-policy-team\" target=\"_blank\">Heavy hitters in Jim Kenney\'s new policy team</a></li>\r\n</ul>\r\nGiven his evolution, several\r\n\r\nLooking at recent polls, we felt Kenney had a winning chance of becoming our next Mayor. Except for the fact that he had Phil Rinaldi, the man behind the dirty energy hub plan, on his advisory team.\r\n\r\nSo a coalition of people against the dirty energy hub, against pipelines, against oil trains, and against fracking met with Kenney.  It was a team representing interfaith groups, environmental groups, labor &amp; business too.  And we\'ve worked with the Kenney team to craft an energy policy for Philadelphia.\r\n\r\nWe\'re pleased with the result, which includes a goal of 80% carbon reduction by 2050. And pleased too that Kenney\'s for an open &amp; democratic process for our energy future.  And that he agreed to add people we recommended to his policy team: a public health person, a scientist, and a clean energy person, right alongside Mr Rinaldi.\r\n\r\nWho are we? 350Philly, Clean Water Action, Neighborhood Networks, PennEnvironment, Interfaith Power &amp; Light, Sierra Club\r\n\r\nAll working to stop the dirty energy hub, to stop pipelines, to stop explosive oil trains, to stop fracking.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nHe\'s evolved. And stepping up to the times.  We can continue wringing our hands and complaining about inaction and corruption from our politicians. Or we can engage in conversation with them, and make this the Climate Change election.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.theecologist.org/blogs_and_comments/commentators/2851231/this_ought_to_be_the_climate_change_election_so_why_isnt_it.html\" target=\"_blank\">This ought to be the Climate Change election</a>.  Let\'s make it one.  Vote for Kenney.\r\n\r\n- gather articles abt Kenney\r\n- show he listens and cares\r\n- show his evolution\r\n- list env orgs endorsing him\r\n- photo w muslim leaders\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;','the Climate election in Philadelphia','','inherit','open','open','','246-revision-v1','','','2015-05-13 12:21:39','2015-05-13 12:21:39','',246,'http://brightphillyfuture.bowersad.com/index.php/2015/05/13/246-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(250,2,'2015-05-13 14:46:09','2015-05-13 14:46:09','Next Tuesday, May 19th, are the primaries.  Philadelphians, predominantly democratic, get to nominate one of the 6 democratic candidates for our next Mayor. The lineup includes Jim Kenney, Nelson Diaz, Lynne Abraham, Anthony Williams, and Doug Oliver &amp; Milton Street. Whoever wins in the primaries next week in effect becomes our next Mayor after the November elections. Of the 6, Jim Kenney rises to the top.\r\n\r\nHow?\r\n\r\nHe\'s local.\r\n\r\nHe\'s experienced around City Hall. On May 11th, the Daily News <a href=\"http://www.philly.com/philly/news/politics/mayor/20150511_DN_Editorial__DAILY_NEWS_ENDORSEMENT__FOR_MAYOR__JIM_KENNEY.html\" target=\"_blank\">editorial</a> wrote this: \"Kenney has shown himself to be independent, especially when you consider the lack of support for many of his pet causes. He knows how the city and its politics work, and is smart and open to new ideas.\"\r\n\r\nHe listens.  Even to people different from him. Examples abound in his openness to LGBT rights, to marijuana reform, to immigration reform. And now, to dealing with climate disruption in our region.  True intelligence is surely demonstrated by patient listening.\r\n\r\nHe listened to us expounding on the moral issues around climate. About creating jobs as well as a clean air, clean water and clean food. About creating an open and democratic process for our energy future. And added a trio of professionals to his policy team: a public health person, a scientist and a clean energy person. We applaud his listening.\r\n\r\nA week earlier, GRID magazine endorsed <a href=\"http://www.gridphilly.com/grid-magazine/2015/4/24/grid-endorses-nelson-diaz-for-mayor.html\">Nelson Diaz for Mayor</a>.  Many of us were disappointed to see this from a local magazine educating our region on sustainability.  We\'ve since realized that this was before the Kenney energy policy was public. The Kenney policy is much better, we think. And, last we heard, Diaz only had 4% at the polls.  Remember that voting for Diaz is stealing a vote from Kenney, and handing it to the Anthony Williams, financed by the fracking industry and anti-Muslim voices.  This was explained to me in 2 words: Ralph Nader.\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>On May 7th, the Inquirer wrote <a href=\"http://articles.philly.com/2015-05-07/news/61869256_1_jim-kenney-police-brutality-civilian-review-board\" target=\"_blank\">this</a>: Kenney called passionate, loyal to a fault, driven to do right.</li>\r\n	<li>On May 3rd, Philadelphia Magazine article <a href=\"http://www.phillymag.com/news/2015/05/03/jim-kenney-mayor-endorsement/\" target=\"_blank\">The (New) Jim Kenney for Mayor</a></li>\r\n	<li></li>\r\n	<li></li>\r\n	<li></li>\r\n</ul>\r\nLooking at recent polls, we felt Kenney had a winning chance of becoming our next Mayor. Except for the fact that he had Phil Rinaldi, the man behind the dirty energy hub plan, on his advisory team. See the Feb 26th Philadelphia Magazine article <a href=\"http://www.phillymag.com/citified/2015/02/26/heavy-hitters-jim-kenneys-new-policy-team\" target=\"_blank\">Heavy hitters in Jim Kenney\'s new policy team</a>.\r\n\r\nSo a coalition of people against the dirty energy hub, against pipelines, against oil trains, and against fracking met with Kenney.  It was a team representing interfaith groups, environmental groups, labor &amp; business too.  And we\'ve worked with the Kenney team to craft an energy policy for Philadelphia.\r\n\r\nWe\'re pleased with the result, which includes a goal of 80% carbon reduction by 2050. And pleased too that Kenney\'s for an open &amp; democratic process for our energy future.  And that he agreed to add people we recommended to his policy team: a public health person, a scientist, and a clean energy person, right alongside Mr Rinaldi.\r\n\r\nWho are we? 350Philly, the Beehive Design Collective, Be the Change (Phila chapter), Call to the Bar, Clean Water Action, EDGE (Encouraging Development of a Green Economy), Interfaith Power &amp; Light (Phila chapter), Maypop Collective for Climate &amp; Economic Justice, Penn Environment, PHEW! a bike shop, Physicians for Social Responsibility, Practical Energy Solutions, Protecting our Waters, Sierra Club (PA chapter), Transition Philadelphia.\r\n\r\nAll working to stop the dirty energy hub, to stop pipelines, to stop explosive oil trains, to stop fracking. And to build a clean energy economy for our region.\r\n\r\nHe\'s evolved. And stepping up to the times.  We can continue wringing our hands and complaining about inaction on climate and corruption from our politicians. Or we can engage in conversation with them, and make this <a href=\"http://www.theecologist.org/blogs_and_comments/commentators/2851231/this_ought_to_be_the_climate_change_election_so_why_isnt_it.html\" target=\"_blank\">the Climate Change election it ought to be</a>.\r\n\r\nVote Kenney for Mayor!','the Climate election in Philadelphia','','inherit','open','open','','246-revision-v1','','','2015-05-13 14:46:09','2015-05-13 14:46:09','',246,'http://brightphillyfuture.bowersad.com/index.php/2015/05/13/246-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(251,2,'2015-05-13 14:58:31','2015-05-13 14:58:31','Next Tuesday, May 19th, are the primaries.  Philadelphians, predominantly democratic, get to nominate one of the 6 democratic candidates for our next Mayor. The lineup includes Jim Kenney, Nelson Diaz, Lynne Abraham, Anthony Williams, and Doug Oliver &amp; Milton Street. Whoever wins in the primaries next week in effect becomes our next Mayor after the November elections. Of the 6, Jim Kenney rises to the top.\r\n\r\nHe\'s local.  Born, schooled, and worked in this city.\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>On May 7th, the Inquirer wrote <a href=\"http://articles.philly.com/2015-05-07/news/61869256_1_jim-kenney-police-brutality-civilian-review-board\" target=\"_blank\">this</a>: Kenney called passionate, loyal to a fault, driven to do right.</li>\r\n	<li>On May 3rd, Philadelphia Magazine article <a href=\"http://www.phillymag.com/news/2015/05/03/jim-kenney-mayor-endorsement/\" target=\"_blank\">The (New) Jim Kenney for Mayor</a></li>\r\n</ul>\r\nHe\'s experienced around City Hall. The recent May 11th Daily News <a href=\"http://www.philly.com/philly/news/politics/mayor/20150511_DN_Editorial__DAILY_NEWS_ENDORSEMENT__FOR_MAYOR__JIM_KENNEY.html\" target=\"_blank\">editorial</a> wrote this: \"Kenney has shown himself to be independent, especially when you consider the lack of support for many of his pet causes. He knows how the city and its politics work, and is smart and open to new ideas.\"\r\n\r\nHe listens.  Even 